Is social media seriously harming our mental health? What do you think? In today‚Äôs blog post (link in bio or story) I‚Äôm voicing my opinion on the topic, touching on the below and the effects social media has on me personally. 
Be happy in real life. Not just on Instagram. 
Be real. Be you. Fuck the haters! 
Don‚Äôt play the comparison game. It never ends well and often leads us to feel more insecure, down and generally deflated with our own lives. 
Don‚Äôt be a dick. Zero tolerance for trolling. Remember you have no idea that someone might be struggling. 
If accounts are making you feel anxious, depressed or sad just go on a unfollow spree and don‚Äôt feel guilty about it. It‚Äôs your Instagram and you can be selective with what you want to see. 
Have people become too sensitive and touchy? It‚Äôs hard to feel like you can 100% be yourself without someone calling you out and taking offence. 
The enormous expectations that grow with Instagram as the platform evolves. Or do people actually not care about more aesthetically pleasing content? ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è I‚Äôve also linked this pink suit (gifted) with @liketoknow.it  so make sure you‚Äôre either;

AD - In the words of fashion psychologist Karen Pine ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt dress for other people, I dress for myself‚Äù I recently went to a talk hosted by @comfortuk which completely opened my eyes to how we view our clothes. Whilst there is nothing more comforting than curling up in a cosy hoody and joggers. For me, I feel my most confident when I‚Äôm wearing bright colours in varying textures like this sweatshirt and silky midi skirt. It uplifts my mood, reflects my personality and is a very ‚Äòme‚Äô outfit.  As a result I feel more positive and ready to take on the day. You may have seen me get a bit riled up recently over a comment a girl posted on my Instagram. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs so sad seeing any influencer that‚Äôs supposed to promote healthy life (gym and healthy food) being posing with a Big Mac (dudes, of course she did not have a bite of that either üí©)UNFOLLOW!‚Äù. It actually spurred me on to write today‚Äôs blog post (link in bio) titled ‚Äòthe epitome of balance‚Äô which I can confidently say I‚Äôve got down to a t. 
It‚Äôs peoples negative attitudes as classing things like burgers and cakes as ‚Äòguilty‚Äô or ‚Äòunhealthy‚Äô that lead many girls to feel infact guilty when eating these foods and can often be the trigger to developing eating disorders. I‚Äôd much rather follow a blogger who lives a healthy lifestyle, works out and yes eats a burger üçî than those who promote slimming teas, skinny this and lose weight that and essentially profit off young girls insecurities of low self esteem and body confidence. Wouldn‚Äôt you? 
Yes I have a fitness page @gemmatalbotfitness üí™üèº but it‚Äôs ridiculous that I should be held to such a high standard of eating. Plus I‚Äôve never claimed to be a PT or nutrionist nor would I want to be. I do everything in life for me and nobody else. Ever heard of the term ‚Äòeat a burger to keep you sane‚Äô üôãüèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èü§∑üèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è granted I don‚Äôt eat one every day but when I do I enjoy every last bite üôÉ
